Semilarski against the Prosecutor’s office: the cassation of the former Vice-Mayor of Tartu will be considered on August 4
This means that a decision on it is likely to be made in early September.
The courts of the two first instances refused to consider Semilarski’s claim, but in April his cassation appeal was accepted by the State Court.
On 12 December 2019, the Tartu Administrative Court returned the complaint to the applicant, as its authorisation was not within the competence of the Administrative Court.
The court decision stated that the complaint contained a claim for compensation for damage caused in the course of criminal proceedings.
“The prosecutor’s office and the district court should regulate such issues,” Tartu Courts spokeswoman Annette Kreitsmann told ERR earlier.
According to her, Valvo Semilarski appealed this decision in the district court, which on February 5 did not change the decision of the court of first instance.
The State Court will now have its say.
According to Semilarski’s lawyer, juror Oliver Nyaes, his client had been under suspicion of bribery for about two years.
Now he demands from the prosecutor’s office to refute the false allegations against him and to compensate him for the moral damage.
The reason for filing the complaint to the court were the statements of the prosecutor for special cases of the Lyuna District Prosecutor’s Office Margus Gross, made by him in October 2017, when Semilarski, together with another at the time, Deputy Mayor of Tartu Artem Suvorov, was detained on suspicion of committing several crimes.
“When I was arrested, the Security Police and the Prosecutor’s Office immediately organized a press conference and informed the entire Republic of Estonia that the leaders of Tartu – one of the most powerful bodies of local self-government – are corrupt.
These public suspicions hung in the air accompanied me for about two years.
And now, when these allegations and suspicions turned out to be false, the prosecutor’s office does not want to say anything about it,” Semilarski commented in early August 2019.
According to Oliver Njaes, at the press conference, the prosecutor went beyond the legal framework within which the prosecutor’s office should operate.
“The allegations of bribery and bribery turned out to be false, but that’s not the only problem here.
The European Court of Human Rights, for example, has repeatedly stressed in its rulings on Russia, as well as on Lithuania, that at the stage of the investigation, representatives of the state should be careful when choosing words, so that suspects are not represented as criminals before sentencing.
The prosecutor’s office is bound by the presumption of innocence, which, unfortunately, was not respected in this case against Valvo Semilarski,” Njaes said.
“The public presentation of Semilarski as a serious offender and a briber in circumstances where the facts underlying the suspicion of bribery are still being clarified is unacceptable, which contradicts the presumption of innocence and is unfair to the applicant,” the lawyer added.
According to rus.err.ee, former Deputy Mayor of Tartu Valvo Semilarski will not be prosecuted on charges of bribery - the criminal case against him in July was partially closed.
At the same time, the former official is being tried on charges of knowingly violating anti-corruption legislation when conducting transactions on a particularly large scale.
According to the indictment, in the period from 2015 to 2017, the former Deputy Mayor of Tartu more than thirty times participated in the meetings of the city administration in making decisions related to companies operating in Tartu, with the owners or managers of which Semilarski actively communicated on a personal level during off-hours.
According to Gross, in all these cases, Semilarski had personal interests, and therefore he had to withdraw from participation in decision-making.
Earlier, as reported by rus.err.ee, the prosecutor's office has presented Semilarski suspicions of receiving a bribe and violation of anti-corruption legislation when conducting transactions on a particularly large scale.
This happened in October 2016, when he was detained along with another deputy mayor, Artem Suvorov (Centre Party).
The prosecutor’s office and the security police said there was strong evidence against the two vice-mayors.
After that, both officials resigned.
Suvorov’s case later went to court, which fully justified the politician.
The trial in the case of Valvo Semilarski is still ongoing.
