How the decision of the Central Bank to reduce the key rate will affect the economy
The Bank of Russia is expected to lower the key rate again.
It fell by another 0.25 percentage point, to 4.25% per annum - formally the next historical minimum.
Judging by the return of the short step of lowering the rate, as well as the tone of the Central Bank's statements and updated forecasts for the Russian economy, the regulator looks at the economic prospects more optimistic than before.
This means that the current cycle of monetary easing may soon stop.
“We have continued easing monetary policy, first of all, given that the risks of inflation deviating from 4% in 2021 still remain,” Elvira Nabiullina, head of the Bank of Russia, said in a statement.
They are associated with a significant decrease in economic activity, a drop in domestic and external demand.
The economic recovery, according to Nabiullina, will take more than a year and a half.
At the same time, she noted that after the lifting of restrictions due to the pandemic, economic processes were revived: energy consumption, consumer and investment demand were restored, construction and production of consumer goods were expanded, the annual rate of decline in transport turnover and industrial production slowed down.
According to the updated forecast of the Central Bank, in 2020 the contraction of the economy will be 4.5-5.5% (previously expected 4-6%), and the recovery growth of the economy in 2021 will be 3.5-4.5%, in 2022 - 2.5-3.5%.
In addition, the Bank of Russia revised the forecast for annual oil prices to $ 38 and $ 40 per barrel of Urals in 2020 and 2021, respectively.
Earlier, the Central Bank expected $ 27 and $ 35 per barrel.
Finally, the Bank of Russia’s inflation forecast for 2020 was 3.7-4.2% against the previously expected 3.8-4.8%.
The Bank of Russia’s view of the situation in the economy is becoming more optimistic, which brings us closer to the end of the easing cycle, according to economists for Russia and the CIS Renaissance Capital Sofia Donets and Andrei Melashchenko.
Thus, the Bank of Russia consistently reduces the key rate for more than a year, since the beginning of last summer it has already fallen by 3.5 percentage points.
And at the last meeting in June, the Central Bank lowered it by one percentage point due to low inflation due to subdued demand and the need to stimulate the economy slowed down due to the pandemic and related restrictions.
The chances of adjusting monetary policy remain (at the next meeting on September 18 and until the end of the year), but the limit is already close, agrees chief analyst of Rosbank Evgeny Koshelev.
The combination of pro-inflationary risks also points to the proximity of a pause in interest-rate easing – disrupted supply chains, possible cost increases due to epidemic prevention measures, and a faster (than expected) recovery in demand, he says.
In conclusion, the Bank of Russia’s subsequent actions will require more attention to inflationary processes during the harvest season, as well as external volatility, which has increased against the background of geopolitical conflicts, Koshelev points out.
One way or another, the reduction in the key rate will lead to a further reduction in rates for the most reliable borrowers, as well as, perhaps, on the mortgage, says Maxim Petronevich, a senior economist at the analytical department of Otkritie Bank.
The correction of rates will be less pronounced than the reduction of the key rate, he clarifies.
Interest rates on loans may fall by another 0.3-0.6 percentage points during the second half of the year, mortgage rates may end the year in the range of 6.2-7%, does not exclude the economist of BCS Prime Anton Pokatovich.
Average rates on deposits, in his opinion, will also fall - in the coming months they can fall to 4.2-4.5% (now barely above 4.5%).
Further, they can fall to 4%, if the Central Bank will reduce the key rate in the fall, says Pokatovich.
