A native of Rwanda admitted that he set fire to the cathedral in Nantes
A Rwandan man who worked at the cathedral of Saints Peter and Paul in the French city of Nantes on a voluntary basis admitted to arson a week after the fire.
This was reported on Sunday by the TV channel “France-3”.
According to him, the man, who was already detained on July 19, the day after the fire, was detained again the day before.
He appeared before the investigating judge on Saturday evening.
After being charged with wilful damage to property, the man admitted that he had set fire to three places - under a large organ, under a small organ and at the electric shield.
Now he faces up to 10 years in prison and a fine of 150 thousand euros.
The motives of the 39-year-old man from Rwanda have not yet been disclosed.
It is known only that he voluntarily helped in the cathedral and on the day of the fire had to close its doors.
However, according to CCTV footage, he left the religious institution 15 minutes after receiving calls about a fire in the building.
The fire in the Cathedral of St. Peter and Paul occurred on July 18.
More than 200 firefighters fought for several hours for a monument of Gothic architecture.
However, they failed to save the stained glass windows of Louis XII and the unique organ of the Baroque era.
The situation was brought under control only three hours after the start of the fire.
No one was injured as a result of the incident.
This is not the first fire in the temple’s history.
In 1972, a fire destroyed the roof.
It took 13 years to eliminate the effects of the fire.
For parishioners, the cathedral was reopened only in 1985.
