The actor of the Russian series responded to accusations of “propaganda of LGBT and feminism”
The actor of the Russian series “Chickey”, the creators of which were accused of “propaganda of LGBT and feminism”, responded to the claims to the film.
The authors “understood the acuteness of the topics raised and did not want to offend anyone,” said the American Steven Thomas Oxner in an interview with the publication “Rise”.
“I think it’s a story about power and the general aspects of human life.
It has nothing to do with LGBT and feminism,” said the actor, who played the father of a boy who dressed up as a woman.
He said he was “proud of his work” and did not see it as propaganda.
At the same time, the American added, he is frightened by the reaction of some people to the storyline of the series: for example, there was a case when "a man in a deep coma shot the set and said that all this is not true."
“Then there were a couple of cases when we met disgruntled locals who did not understand what we were doing.
But we were open, so the people who first came with claims began to help us,” he concluded.
The case of the shooting, the newspaper explains, occurred in September 2019 in Kabardino-Balkaria: a drunk man attacked the car of a film crew with weapons, after which he was detained by police officers.
